Two separate issues here:

## 1. `StaticResource` won't update at runtime

`StaticResource` resolves **once** at XAML load time. Switch to `DynamicResource` so bindings re-evaluate when you swap the `ResourceDictionary`:

```xml
<!-- ✗ won't update -->
<Label TextColor="{StaticResource PrimaryTextColor}" />

<!-- ✓ updates when the dictionary changes -->
<Label TextColor="{DynamicResource PrimaryTextColor}" />
```

Then swap themes in code by replacing the merged dictionary:

```csharp
var mergedDicts = Application.Current.Resources.MergedDictionaries;
mergedDicts.Clear();
mergedDicts.Add(useDark ? new DarkTheme() : new LightTheme());
```

## 2. Android restarts on dark-mode toggle

By default Android **recreates the Activity** on a `uiMode` configuration change. Tell Android your app handles it itself by adding `ConfigChanges.UiMode` to your `MainActivity`:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
[Activity(
    Theme = "@style/Maui.SplashTheme",
    ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                         | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                         | ConfigChanges.UiMode  // ← add this
                         | ConfigChanges.ScreenLayout
                         | ConfigChanges.SmallestScreenSize)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

With `UiMode` declared, Android won't destroy/recreate the activity. You can then detect the OS change and apply your theme:

```csharp
// App.xaml.cs
Application.Current.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    bool dark = e.RequestedTheme == AppTheme.Dark;
    var merged = Resources.MergedDictionaries;
    merged.Clear();
    merged.Add(dark ? new DarkTheme() : new LightTheme());
};
```

**TL;DR** — `DynamicResource` for runtime updates, `ConfigChanges.UiMode` to stop the restart.
